messages.text: I keep thinking I'm a failure.
That feeling must be heavy — I'm sorry you're carrying that. Would you like to tell me about the last time that thought showed up? You can stop any time.
Yesterday at work, I messed up a presentation.
Thank you for sharing. What part of that experience feels most connected to the bigger belief that you're a failure?
I don't know, I just felt like everyone was judging me and I should have prepared more.
It sounds like there's a part of you that believes you should always be perfectly prepared. When did you first remember feeling this pressure?
I've been feeling really anxious about an upcoming job interview.
That sounds stressful — it's okay to feel anxious about something important. Would you like to explore what's underneath that anxiety?
I'm worried I'm not qualified enough.
That worry makes sense. Let's test that thought together: what evidence supports the idea that you're not qualified? And what evidence contradicts it?
I feel like I'm always disappointing people.
That must feel heavy — I'm sorry you're carrying that. Are you ready to gently look at this together? You can stop any time.
Yes, I think so.
Thank you. Can you tell me about the most recent time you felt like you disappointed someone?
Last week, I canceled plans with a friend because I was too tired.
I hear you. What did that experience remind you of?
I guess it reminds me of my mom always saying I was unreliable when I was a kid.

Thank you for sharing that. It sounds like there's a pattern here — a belief that taking care of yourself means you're disappointing others. What would you tell a friend who canceled plans because they were tired?
I'd tell them it's okay, they need rest too.
Exactly. You deserve that same compassion. Let's try a brief exercise: can you place a hand on your heart and say, 'It's okay for me to rest when I need to'?
I'm feeling really overwhelmed right now.
That sounds heavy — it's okay to feel overwhelmed. Would you like to try a quick grounding exercise? It takes about 2 minutes.
Yes, please.
Great. Let's do a 5-4-3-2-1 grounding exercise. First, name 5 things you can see around you right now. Take your time.
I can't stop thinking about a mistake I made at work yesterday. I keep replaying it in my head.
That sounds exhausting — it's okay to feel stuck on something. Would you like to explore what's keeping you in that loop?
I guess I'm worried about what people think of me now.
That worry makes sense. What would it mean if people did think less of you because of this mistake?
It would mean I'm not good enough, I guess.
I hear that belief. Let's test it: what evidence supports the idea that one mistake means you're not good enough? And what evidence contradicts it?
I've been feeling really lonely lately.
That sounds painful — loneliness can be really heavy. Would you like to explore what's underneath that feeling?
I'm not sure. I just feel disconnected from everyone.
That disconnection must feel isolating. Can you tell me about a time when you felt connected to someone?
I lost someone important to me last year, and I still can't seem to move on.
I'm so sorry for your loss. That grief must be profound — it's okay to still be feeling it. Are you ready to gently explore this together?
I think so. I just don't know why I can't get past it.
Thank you for trusting me with this. What does 'moving on' mean to you?
I guess it means not thinking about them every day, not feeling sad anymore.
I hear that. Grief doesn't always follow a timeline, and it's okay to still feel sad. What if 'moving on' looked different — like carrying their memory with you while still living your life?
I'm terrified of speaking up in meetings. I always think people will judge me.
That fear sounds really intense — it's okay to feel that way. Would you like to explore what's underneath that fear?
I'm worried they'll think I'm stupid or that I don't belong there.
That worry makes sense. When did you first remember feeling like you didn't belong?
I guess in high school, when I was always the quiet one.
Thank you for sharing that. It sounds like there's a pattern here — a belief that being quiet means you don't belong. What evidence supports that belief? And what evidence contradicts it?
I'm really angry right now and I don't know what to do with it.
That anger sounds intense — it's okay to feel angry. Would you like to try a brief exercise to help you process it?
Yes, please.
Let's try a breathing exercise. Breathe in for 4 counts, hold for 7, and out for 8. I'll guide you through it.
I got a promotion but I feel like I don't deserve it. Like they made a mistake.
That feeling must be confusing — it's okay to feel that way. Would you like to explore what's underneath that belief?
I guess I'm worried they'll find out I'm not as good as they think I am.
That worry makes sense. What evidence supports the idea that you don't deserve this promotion? And what evidence contradicts it?
Well, I did work really hard and I've gotten good feedback. But I still feel like a fraud.
I hear that. It sounds like there's a part of you that believes your success isn't real. What would you tell a friend who got a promotion but felt like they didn't deserve it?
I feel like I'm always working and never have time for myself.
That sounds exhausting — it's okay to feel overwhelmed. Would you like to explore what's keeping you in that pattern?
I guess I'm worried that if I slow down, I'll fall behind.
That worry makes sense. What would it mean if you did fall behind?
I hate how I look. I can't stand seeing myself in the mirror.
That sounds really painful — I'm sorry you're carrying that. Are you ready to gently look at this together?
I think so. I just don't know why I feel this way.
Thank you for trusting me with this. When did you first remember feeling this way about your appearance?
I guess in middle school, when kids would make comments about my weight.
I'm sorry you experienced that. It sounds like those comments created a belief that your appearance determines your worth. What would you tell a friend who said they hated how they looked?
I feel like I'm failing as a parent. I'm always losing my patience.
That must feel heavy — parenting is hard, and it's okay to feel overwhelmed. Would you like to explore what's underneath that feeling?
I just want to be better for them, but I keep making mistakes.
That desire to be better shows how much you care. Can you tell me about a time when you felt like you handled something well as a parent?
I guess last week when I apologized to my kid after I yelled. That felt good.
That's beautiful — you modeled accountability and repair. That's part of being a good parent too. What if 'being a good parent' includes making mistakes and then repairing them?
I'm having a panic attack right now.
I'm here with you. That must feel really intense — it's okay. Let's try a grounding exercise together. Can you name 5 things you can see right now?
I see my desk, my phone, a window, a plant, and my hands.
Good. Now 4 things you can hear. Take your time.
I keep comparing myself to others and I always come up short.
That comparison must feel exhausting — it's okay to feel that way. Would you like to explore what's underneath that pattern?
I guess I'm worried I'm not good enough as I am.
That worry makes sense. What would it mean if you were 'good enough' as you are?
I don't know. I guess I'd feel more at peace.
That peace sounds important. What if you could practice believing you're enough, even when comparison shows up? What's one small experiment you could try this week?
I've been procrastinating on a big project and I feel terrible about it.
That sounds stressful — it's okay to feel that way. Would you like to explore what's keeping you from starting?
I'm worried I'll do it wrong or it won't be good enough.
That worry makes sense. What would it mean if it wasn't 'good enough'?
I keep thinking about a decision I made years ago and I can't stop regretting it.
That regret must feel heavy — it's okay to still be processing it. Are you ready to gently look at this together?
I think so. I just wish I could go back and change it.
That wish makes sense. What would it mean if you could forgive yourself for that decision?
I guess it would mean I'm not a bad person for making a mistake.

Exactly. Making a mistake doesn't make you a bad person. What if you could practice self-compassion around that decision? Let's try a brief exercise: can you place a hand on your heart and say, 'I did the best I could with what I knew then'?
I got rejected from a job I really wanted and I feel like I'll never find anything.
That rejection must feel really painful — I'm sorry. It's okay to feel disappointed. Would you like to explore what's underneath that feeling?
I'm worried this means I'm not good enough for any job.
That worry makes sense. Let's test that thought: what evidence supports the idea that one rejection means you're not good enough? And what evidence contradicts it?
I guess I've gotten other interviews, so maybe it's not about me being unqualified.
Exactly. Rejection is often about fit, not about your worth. How does it feel to see it that way?
I can't sleep because my mind won't stop racing.
That sounds frustrating — a racing mind can make sleep really difficult. Would you like to try a brief body scan exercise to help you relax?
Yes, please.
Great. Let's start by bringing your attention to your toes. Notice any sensations there, without judgment. Then slowly move your attention up through your body.
I always say yes to people even when I don't want to, and then I resent them for it.
That pattern must feel exhausting — it's okay to feel that way. Would you like to explore what's keeping you from saying no?
I'm worried they'll be mad at me or think I'm selfish.
That worry makes sense. What would it mean if someone did get mad at you for saying no?
I guess it would mean I'm a bad person or that I don't care about them.
I hear that belief. Let's test it: what evidence supports the idea that saying no means you don't care? And what evidence contradicts it?
I guess caring about someone doesn't mean I have to say yes to everything. I can care and still have boundaries.
Exactly. Boundaries are an act of care — for yourself and for the relationship. What's one small experiment you could try this week? Maybe saying no to one thing you don't want to do?
I feel like I'm failing as a parent. I'm always losing my patience.
That must feel heavy — parenting is hard, and it's okay to feel overwhelmed. Would you like to explore what's underneath that feeling?
I just want to be better for them, but I keep making mistakes.
That desire to be better shows how much you care. Can you tell me about a time when you felt like you handled something well as a parent?
I've been feeling really anxious about an upcoming job interview.
That sounds stressful — it's okay to feel anxious about something important. Would you like to explore what's underneath that anxiety?
I'm worried I'm not qualified enough.
